  "translations": {
    "en": {
      "description": {
        "text": "A very high and impressive crag in an open, sunny and beautiful setting. One of Stockholm’s best crags for long routes in the 7a–8a range. The bolting used to be rather adventurous, but most routes have now been rebolted and are safe to climb.",
        "method": "llm",
        "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
        "sourceIds": [
          "legacy:dodskalleberget"
        ]
      },
      "sections": {
        "allmant": {
          "title": {
            "text": "General",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "A very high and impressive crag in an open, sunny and beautiful setting. One of Stockholm’s best crags for long routes in the 7a–8a range. The bolting used to be adventurous, but most routes have now been rebolted and are safe to climb.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          }
        },
        "miljo": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Conditions",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "The crag becomes unbearably hot in summer. Best in early spring and late autumn, and sometimes even on fine winter days! The right-hand side of the main wall stays reasonably dry in the rain. Swimming rocks within walking distance.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          }
        },
        "vagbeskrivning": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Directions",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "Take Tyresövägen out onto the Tyresö peninsula and continue straight ahead for quite some way along the winding road until you reach a small marina. Turn right and continue for some distance along a hilly road. After a steep descent, turn right onto Dyviksuddsvägen. The crag can be seen on the right after a couple of hundred metres. Park in the car park about 150 m beyond the crag. The car park is well used, so leave room for other cars. The recently established Dyviks lövängar nature reserve surrounds the crag and is now signposted. The crag forms part of the reserve.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          }
        },
        "access": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Access",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "Climbing is under constant threat of being banned. Be discreet, do not litter and keep a low profile. The crag lies within the Dyviks lövängar nature reserve. Park only in the car park about 150 m beyond the crag, and position your car so that more vehicles can fit.\n\nIn 2012, the Stockholm Bolt Committee reached an agreement with Tyresö Municipality, which manages the nature reserve, regarding the rebolting of routes. Rebolting is permitted only under certain conditions, and every action must be approved by the municipality through a written procedure.\n\nhttp://bultkommitten.blogspot.se/2012/09/dodskalleberget-bultas-om.html",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          }
        },
        "leder": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Routes",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:dodskalleberget"
            ]
          },
